------------------------------------------------------------------------------
PG_UPGRADE: IN-PLACE UPGRADES FOR POSTGRESQL
------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Upgrading a PostgreSQL database from one major release to another can be
an expensive process. For minor upgrades, you can simply install new
executables and forget about upgrading existing data. But for major
upgrades, you have to export all of your data using pg_dump, install the
new release, run initdb to create a new cluster, and then import your
old data. If you have a lot of data, that can take a considerable amount
of time. If you have too much data, you may have to buy more storage
since you need enough room to hold the original data plus the exported
data.  pg_upgrade can reduce the amount of time and disk space required
for many upgrades.

The URL http://momjian.us/main/writings/pgsql/pg_upgrade.pdf contains a
presentation about pg_upgrade internals that mirrors the text
description below.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------
WHAT IT DOES
------------------------------------------------------------------------------

pg_upgrade is a tool that performs an in-place upgrade of existing
data. Some upgrades change the on-disk representation of data;
pg_upgrade cannot help in those upgrades.  However, many upgrades do
not change the on-disk representation of a user-defined table.  In those
cases, pg_upgrade can move existing user-defined tables from the old
database cluster into the new cluster.

There are two factors that determine whether an in-place upgrade is
practical.

Every table in a cluster shares the same on-disk representation of the
table headers and trailers and the on-disk representation of tuple
headers. If this changes between the old version of PostgreSQL and the
new version, pg_upgrade cannot move existing tables to the new cluster;
you will have to pg_dump the old data and then import that data into the
new cluster.

Second, all data types should have the same binary representation
between the two major PostgreSQL versions.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------
HOW IT WORKS
------------------------------------------------------------------------------

To use pg_upgrade during an upgrade, start by installing a fresh
cluster using the newest version in a new directory. When you've
finished installation, the new cluster will contain the new executables
and the usual template0, template1, and postgres databases, but no
user-defined tables. At this point, you can shut down the old and new
postmasters and invoke pg_upgrade.

When pg_upgrade starts, it ensures that all required executables are
present and contain the expected version numbers. The verification
process also checks the old and new $PGDATA directories to ensure that
the expected files and subdirectories are in place.  If the verification
process succeeds, pg_upgrade starts the old postmaster and runs
pg_dumpall --schema-only to capture the metadata contained in the old
cluster. The script produced by pg_dumpall will be used in a later step
to recreate all user-defined objects in the new cluster.

Note that the script produced by pg_dumpall will only recreate
user-defined objects, not system-defined objects.  The new cluster will
contain the system-defined objects created by the latest version of
PostgreSQL.

Once pg_upgrade has extracted the metadata from the old cluster, it
performs a number of bookkeeping tasks required to 'sync up' the new
cluster with the existing data.

First, pg_upgrade copies the commit status information and 'next
transaction ID' from the old cluster to the new cluster. This step
ensures that the proper tuples are visible from the new cluster.
Remember, pg_upgrade does not export/import the content of user-defined
tables so the transaction IDs in the new cluster must match the
transaction IDs in the old data. pg_upgrade also copies the starting
address for write-ahead logs from the old cluster to the new cluster.

Now pg_upgrade begins reconstructing the metadata obtained from the old
cluster using the first part of the pg_dumpall output.

Next, pg_upgrade executes the remainder of the script produced earlier
by pg_dumpall --- this script effectively creates the complete
user-defined metadata from the old cluster to the new cluster.  It
preserves the relfilenode numbers so TOAST and other references
to relfilenodes in user data is preserved.  (See binary-upgrade usage
in pg_dump). We choose to preserve tablespace and database OIDs as well.

Finally, pg_upgrade links or copies each user-defined table and its
supporting indexes and toast tables from the old cluster to the new
cluster.

An important feature of the pg_upgrade design is that it leaves the
original cluster intact --- if a problem occurs during the upgrade, you
can still run the previous version, after renaming the tablespaces back
to the original names.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------
LEE: --initdb OPTION
------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Normally pg_upgrade requires the user to create the new cluster manually
with initdb before running pg_upgrade.  The --initdb option automates
this step: pg_upgrade runs initdb on the new data directory, propagating
the locale, encoding, WAL segment size, and checksum settings from the
old cluster so the two clusters are compatible.

The --initdb option uses pg_controldata output from the old cluster to
derive the correct initdb parameters.  Specifically it mirrors:

  --encoding          (from the old cluster's template0 database)
  --locale-provider   (builtin, libc, or icu)
  --builtin-locale / --icu-locale / --locale  (from the old cluster)
  --lc-collate, --lc-ctype
  --wal-segsize       (from the old cluster's WAL segment size)
  --data-checksums    (if the old cluster uses checksums)
  --char-signedness   (if the old and new versions differ on the default)

Without --initdb the new cluster must already exist in the directory
named by -D / --new-datadir before pg_upgrade is invoked.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------
LEE: --wal-log-upgrade OPTION
------------------------------------------------------------------------------

By default pg_upgrade physically transfers user relation files and copies
the old cluster's SLRU (pg_xact, pg_multixact) into the new cluster, none
of which is WAL-logged, and then destroys the restore WAL with pg_resetwal.
The upgrade is therefore not crash-safe and cannot be replayed.

--wal-log-upgrade makes the whole upgrade atomic and WAL-replayable, and
"skips the disk writes" so that recovery is genuinely verifiable: every
byte the upgrade would have written to the new cluster's data files is
instead captured as full-page images in WAL, the on-disk copies are then
reverted to an empty baseline, and first startup reconstructs the entire
cluster purely from WAL.  If any image were missing the data would come
back wrong, so a correct startup proves the WAL is self-sufficient.

GENERATE ALL UPGRADE WAL AT THE END
-----------------------------------

The upgrade server runs at wal_level=replica (initdb's default; not lowered to
minimal).  Only after ALL pg_upgrade work is complete (schema restore, file
transfer, counter transplant) does pg_upgrade, with the server still running,
generate its own WAL as one atomic burst (pg_upgrade.c).  Running at replica
means the burst -- and the persisted pg_control -- are at a level a standby can
recover from:

  1. CHECKPOINT + pg_flush_upgrade_slru()  -- flush every dirty buffer and
     SLRU page so the on-disk images are the authoritative final state
  2. pg_write_pg_upgrade_start()           -- XLOG_PG_UPGRADE_START marker
  3. pg_write_upgrade_dirskel()            -- XLOG_UPGRADE_DIRSKEL: after-image
     of the initdb directory tree (so replay recreates the skeleton)
  4. pg_write_upgrade_relfile_data()       -- FPI of every relation file
  5. pg_write_upgrade_slru_data(0/1/2)     -- FPI of pg_xact and pg_multixact
  6. pg_write_pg_upgrade_complete()        -- XLOG_PG_UPGRADE_COMPLETE marker
  7. pg_switch_wal()                       -- seal the segment

The XID/OID/multixact counters are NOT a WAL record.  They are transplanted
into pg_control with stock pg_resetwal BEFORE the CHECKPOINT above (which is
why the server is restarted just before it), so the CN checkpoint record
already carries them and recovery reproduces every counter for free.  This is
exactly what stock pg_upgrade ends up with -- verified: the OID/XID/multixact
counters after a --wal-log-upgrade match a normal pg_upgrade of the same data
bit for bit.

Emitting at the end (after all transactions have committed and been
checkpointed) is what keeps MVCC visibility correct: the captured SLRU
image is the final, merged commit state, so replaying it can never make a
committed transaction look in-progress.

Records are emitted at the coarsest granularity that fits a WAL record
(XLogRecordMaxSize = 1020 MB).  SLRU segments are packed several to a
record; a relation-file segment larger than the limit (a full 1 GB segment
is 1024 MB) is split into page-aligned chunks, each carrying its starting
block offset within the segment.

RECOVERY ANCHOR: THE END-OF-UPGRADE CHECKPOINT (CN), NOT C0
-----------------------------------------------------------

Recovery is anchored at CN -- the checkpoint taken at step 1 above, right
before the image burst -- NOT at the initdb checkpoint (C0).  Replay therefore
starts after all of pg_restore's work and applies ONLY the end-of-upgrade
images; it never re-runs pg_restore's WAL.  This matters because pg_restore
creates databases with the CREATE DATABASE FILE_COPY strategy, whose redo
copies the template databases' files from disk -- which would be impossible
once those files are wiped.

CN is an online checkpoint, so its redo pointer precedes the checkpoint record
(PostgreSQL writes an XLOG_CHECKPOINT_REDO marker there).  pg_upgrade captures
both LSNs from pg_control_checkpoint() and passes them to
pg_resetwal --upgrade-recovery=CN,REDO, which sets pg_control.checkPoint = CN
and checkPointCopy.redo = REDO so StartupXLOG() replays from the right point.

SKIP THE DISK WRITES (WIPE THE WHOLE IMAGE)
-------------------------------------------

After stop_postmaster_immediate() (no shutdown checkpoint, WAL intact),
revert_wal_logged_disk_writes() wipes the ENTIRE on-disk data image, since it
is all captured in WAL now:

  - every file in each base/<dboid>/ directory
  - every file in global/ EXCEPT pg_control
  - all pg_xact / pg_multixact segments

Files are unlinked (not truncated) so --link mode does not destroy the old
cluster's data through shared inodes.  What remains on disk is only the empty
directory skeleton, global/pg_control (the entry point recovery needs before
it can read any WAL), and the top-level PG_VERSION (checked by the postmaster
before recovery starts).  The persisted new cluster thus looks like a fresh,
pre-initdb directory tree with empty folders.

RETAIN AND ARM THE WAL
----------------------

The upgrade server runs with wal_keep_size / max_wal_size pinned very high
(server.c) so that no checkpoint recycles any segment of the image burst
before it is preserved (the images are as large as the data itself).  The
counter-transplant pg_resetwal calls are the plain upstream ones (they run
before the image burst, so the WAL they reset is throwaway either way -- no
--control-only, no separate handling).  Finally pg_resetwal
--upgrade-recovery=CN,REDO arms crash recovery.

The upgrade WAL simply STAYS in pg_wal/ -- there is no rename to a side
directory.  The START/COMPLETE records in the WAL are themselves the signal
that an upgrade is pending, and pg_control (checkPoint = CN, DB_IN_PRODUCTION)
drives normal crash recovery.  Keeping the WAL in pg_wal/ is also what lets a
physical standby receive the same records in its WAL stream.

REPLAY ON FIRST STARTUP
-----------------------

PerformWalUpgradeIfNeeded() (pgupgrade_wal.c, before StartupXLOG) scans pg_wal/
for the pg_upgrade markers:

  - START + COMPLETE   -> arm the bootstrap; StartupXLOG() crash-recovers from
                          CN through COMPLETE (the whole window applies atomically)
  - START, no COMPLETE -> FATAL "re-run pg_upgrade" (crash mid-upgrade; the old
                          cluster is intact -- a partial window is NEVER applied)
  - no START           -> normal startup

The atomicity guarantee is exactly this: the upgrade is applied only once a
genuine COMPLETE marker is confirmed present; otherwise nothing is applied.

Redo rebuilds every wiped file:

  - XLOG_UPGRADE_DIRSKEL      -> recreates the initdb directory skeleton (the
    logged after-image), so base/<dboid>, the SLRU dirs, etc. exist before any
    file image is replayed into them -- the tree comes from WAL, not from a
    surviving on-disk skeleton
  - XLOG_UPGRADE_RELFILE_DATA -> applied THROUGH the buffer manager, which
    creates the file and its database directory on demand (smgrcreate) and
    stamps the page with the record's LSN so it is flushed by the
    end-of-recovery checkpoint
  - XLOG_UPGRADE_RAWFILE      -> pg_filenode.map and PG_VERSION written
    verbatim (creating parent dirs); these are not buffered relations, so
    they are the only way to rebuild the relation map from empty folders
  - XLOG_UPGRADE_SLRU_DATA    -> installed into the SimpleLru buffers and
    flushed (SlruUpgradeRestoreSegment); the image is emitted last and is the
    final merged CLOG/multixact state, so it is authoritative and is the only
    source of the old cluster's historical commit bits

The XID/OID/multixact counters need no redo: recovery initializes them from
the CN checkpoint record, which already carries the transplanted values.

The result: from just the folder skeleton + pg_control + PG_VERSION + the WAL,
first startup reconstructs the complete upgraded cluster.

PREREQUISITE: THE SKELETON MUST EXIST BEFORE REPLAY
---------------------------------------------------

The directory skeleton is a HARD prerequisite -- recovery does NOT work from a
bare directory containing only pg_control + PG_VERSION + the WAL.  Verified: with
the skeleton removed, startup FATALs with

    could not open directory "pg_notify": No such file or directory

The reason is ordering.  At startup the postmaster initializes runtime
subsystems -- pg_notify (async.c), pg_subtrans, pg_serial (predicate.c),
pg_dynshmem, pg_commit_ts, pg_stat, etc. -- which open their directories
BEFORE, and independently of, WAL replay.  Those directories hold transient
runtime state; nothing WAL-logs them, so XLOG_UPGRADE_DIRSKEL (which runs during
replay, later) cannot supply them in time.  DIRSKEL recreates the DATA
directories (base/<dboid>, the SLRU dirs) that replay writes into; it does not
and cannot substitute for the runtime skeleton the postmaster needs up front.

So the minimum on-disk state required before first startup is:

  - pg_control            (pre-WAL anchor: sysid, CN pointer, DB_IN_PRODUCTION)
  - PG_VERSION            (checked by the postmaster before recovery)
  - the initdb skeleton   (pg_notify, pg_subtrans, pg_wal, config files, ...)
  - the upgrade WAL in pg_wal/

The DATA folders (base/<dboid>, pg_xact, pg_multixact) may be empty or absent --
those are rebuilt from WAL.  But the runtime skeleton and the two anchor files
must pre-exist.  For a spawn-a-fresh-cluster deployment (e.g. a new-version VM /
compute that replays the upgrade WAL), this means the target must lay down an
initdb skeleton (or run initdb) FIRST; handing it a bare directory plus the WAL
will not start.

WAL BYTES COUNTER

pg_upgrade also measures the WAL generated during schema restore via the
pg_upgrade_wal_bytes counter (LogOpts), emitted at PG_VERBOSE level.
